{"id":"materials-around-us-6","label":"Materials Around Us","lockAfter":2,"list":[{"id":"notes","type":"passage","label":"Notes","data":{"title":"Materials Around Us","text":"Any substance that is used to create an object is referred to as material. Freshly cut wood, which is unpolished, has a distinct appearance, quite different from that of iron. Similarly, iron looks different from copper or aluminium. However, there might be some similarities among iron, copper and aluminium that make them different from wood.\n# Lustrous\nMaterials that typically have shiny surfaces are said to have a lustrous appearance. They are usually metals. eg: iron, copper, zinc, aluminium, gold. However, some metals may lose their lustre and start to look dull or non-lustrous due to the effect of air and moisture on them. As a result, we often notice the lustre only on their freshly cut surfaces.\nNon-lustrous materials are those that do not have a shiny surface. eg: paper, wood, rubber, jute\n# Soft & Hard\nMaterials which can be compressed or scratched easily are soft, while other materials which are difficult to compress or scratch are hard. However, these properties are relative in nature. For example, rubber is harder than sponge but softer than iron.\n# Transparent\nThe materials, through which things can be seen clearly, are called transparent. eg: glass, water, air, cellophane paper.\n# Opaque\nThere are many materials through which you are not able to see at all. These materials are called opaque. eg: wood, cardboard, metals\n# Translucent\nThe materials through which objects can be seen, but not clearly, are known as translucent. eg: butter paper, frosted glass\n# Soluble\nYou might have noticed that some materials completely disappear when mixed in water. We say that these materials dissolve in water or, in other words, they are soluble in water.\n# Insoluble\nSome materials do not mix with water and do not disappear even after we stir them for a long time. These materials are insoluble in water.\n# ORS\nOral Rehydration Solution is used to treat dehydration due to diarrhoea or other illnesses. These ready-made ORS packets are available in primary health centres and also in the market. Each packet is dissolved in a litre of water before use. If these are not available, ORS can be prepared at home by mixing six teaspoons of sugar and half a teaspoon of common salt in one litre of boiled and cooled water.\n# Mixing Fluids\nSome liquids get completely mixed with water. Some do not mix with water and form a separate layer when left undisturbed for some time. Similarly, some gases are soluble in water whereas others are not. For example, oxygen gas dissolves in water. It is very important for the survival of animals and plants that live in water.\n# Mass\nAny object can be called heavier or lighter by measuring its property called mass.\n# Volume\nYou may have noticed drinking water bottles of different sizes being sold in the market. You can notice 1 L, 500 mL, 200 mL etc, written as net quantity on the bottles. They indicate the volume of water the bottle can hold.\n# What is Matter?\nMass and volume are the two properties that are possessed by all materials. Anything that occupies space and has mass is called matter. The mass gives the quantity of matter, and the units to measure it are gram (g) and kilogram (kg). The space occupied by matter is its volume. The units to measure the volume are litre (L) and millilitre (mL). "}},{"label":"Fill in the blanks","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"fillup","onlyBigScreen":true,"commonData":{"dashWidth":100,"actWidth":1300,"fontSize":"2rem","dashHeight":"2.7rem","labelsOnSide":true},"data":["Materials with shiny surfaces are called *lustrous*. \nWe can easily see through *transparent* material.\nWe can partially see through *translucent* material.\nWe cannot see through *opaque* material.\nORS solution is used to treat *dehydration* due to *diarrhoea* and other *illness*. ","Soft materials are easy to *compress*.\nThe amount of matter is measured by its *mass*.\nThe space occupied by matter is measured by its *volume*.\nSalt and sugar are *soluble* in water.\nSand and oil are *insoluble* in water.\nOxygen gas *dissolves* in water."]},{"id":"mcq","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"questions":[{"qText":"Which of the following are possessed by all matters?","options":"* volume\nshape\ncolour\n* mass"},{"qText":"Frosted glass is a ______ material","options":"translucent, transparent, Opaque, Soluble"},{"qText":"ORS is used to treat _____.","options":"dehydration, fever, cold, headache"},{"qText":"Heaviness or lightness of a material is measured by its ______.","options":"mass, weight, kilogram, volume"},{"qText":"Lustrous material losses its shine due to _______.","options":"the effect of air and moisture\ndust depositing over them\nthe heat from the sun\nthe sunlight"}]}},{"label":"True or False","id":"true-false","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"Classify the below sentences as true and false","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Soft materials are easily compressed or scratched.\nGas has both mass and volume."},{"name":"False","text":"All liquids are soluble in water. | Oil is not soluble in water.\nLustrous materials loss their shine due to dust depositing over them. | It is due to reaction of air and moisture.\nAnimals living in water doesn't require oxygen.| All living things require oxygen. They consume the oxygen present in water."}]}},{"type":"rightOne","label":"Odd one out","id":"odd-one-out","data":{"title":"Find the odd one out. ","text":"Wood, Iron, Copper, Aluminium \nCotton, Rubber, Sponge, Glass \nPaper, Glass, Air, Water \nSand, Salt, Sugar, Milk Powder \nAir, Cotton, Rubber, Brick ","feedback":"Metals are lustrous, but not wood.\n        Soft materials except glass.\n        Transparent materials except paper.\n        Soluble in water - except sand.\n        Not very heavy materials - except brick."}}]}